Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
2:38 PM Defendant Korei D Wilkins in court.  Attorney Blake Duren in court for Korei D Wilkins.  Prosecuting attorney Michael X. Albrecht in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Court states case and appearances.  State states they are ready to proceed but notes there is an older case which would be included in a global resolution including a PSI.  State requests that both matters be set for plea/sent at a later date as they are both resolved.  Atty Duren is in agreement.  Court makes statement re: the age of the case(s) and notes this case can be done relatively quickly as it is a bailjumping charge.  Court asks questions re: the potential global resolution and what is holding up the train - possible condition precedent.  State notes there is no condition precedent.  Court suggests a plea hearing be set in the next couple of weeks.  Court goes off the record to discuss scheduling.  Back on the record, plea hearing set for both matters on 11/11/22 at 1pm.  Bonds continued.  21CF702 to track.  FPT/MH/Ludwig Hearing also to track to that date.
